# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1984-european-parliament-election-in-france
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/110-propositions-for-france] The social and economic program was dominated by Keynesian measures.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1791-french-legislative-election] Legislative elections were held in France between 29 August and 5 September 1791, the first national elections to the Legislative Assembly.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1791-french-legislative-election] They took place during a period of turmoil caused by the Flight and Arrest at Varennes, the Jacobin split, the Champ-de-Mars Massacre and the Pillnitz Declaration.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1791-french-legislative-election] Suffrage was limited to men paying taxes, although less than 25% of those eligible to do so voted.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1791-french-legislative-election] The Flight to Varennes, also known as the Flight of Louis XVI, on 20 June 1791 caused unrest in the Constituent Assembly and helped to discredit the constitutional monarchy in the eyes of the Parisian patriots.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1791-french-legislative-election] Even though the deputies arrested both Louis XVI and Marie Antoinette the very next day, in the minds of some, the Republic became a possible regime.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1791-french-legislative-election] The Constituante, which on the whole remained monarchist and legalist, declared that Louis XVI had been kidnapped and was therefore not guilty, in response to an influx of petitions calling for the King's deposition.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1791-french-legislative-election] This stance led to a petition being lodged by over 6,000 people on the Champ-de-Mars, while the moderates united in support of the threatened king and, on 17 July 1791, used this demonstration, which had been declared contrary to the Constitution, as a pretext to restore order.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1791-french-legislative-election] However, this return to order led to bloody repression during the Champ-de-Mars massacre.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1791-french-legislative-election] The bloody clash, which claimed 50 victims, created a rift between the democratic revolutionaries and the liberal bourgeoisie; it was the culmination of several months of social convulsions and revolutionary agitation.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1791-french-legislative-election] The day before, supporters of the king and the Constitution had split from the Jacobins and decided to create their own faction in the Rue Saint-Honoré, in the former Convent of the Feuillants, whose name they took.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1791-french-legislative-election] At the same time, Louis XVI was restored to his throne by the decrees of 15 and 16 July 1791.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1791-french-legislative-election] On 14 September 1791, he accepted the revised Constitution, the executive branch of which had been strengthened, and swore an oath of allegiance the following day.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1791-french-legislative-election] The deputies of the Constituent Assembly went their separate ways on 30 September 1791, believing that they had completed the union of royalty and the censorious bourgeoisie against the popular upsurge and the aristocratic counter-revolution.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1791-french-legislative-election] For the vast majority of them, the Revolution was over.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1791-french-legislative-election] In July 1791, the National Constituent Assembly created a constitution committee of 30 members, which drew up a constitution adopted on 3 September.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1791-french-legislative-election] This provided for a 745-seat Legislative Assembly with members elected for a two-year term.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1791-french-legislative-election] The law required the electors to assemble when summoned, to check the credentials of the citizens present, to elect a bureau and then to make appointments.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1791-french-legislative-election] These assemblies were prohibited from deliberating, adopting by-laws, supplementing their choices with instructions or mandatory mandates, and from corresponding with each other.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1791-french-legislative-election] Finally, they had to separate once their work was done.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1791-french-legislative-election] As soon as the results are announced, the elected representatives escape their electors and, regardless of the constituency that elected them, derive their authority from the nation as a whole.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1791-french-legislative-election] This practice allows the elections to take place, like those that follow, in a total political vacuum, i.e. with no publicly debated issues; there is no public competition between candidates, no programme and no declared candidates.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1791-french-legislative-election] This political vacuum, which has become the rule, is leading to the emergence of a debate on political support through illegal organisations, on the fringes and outside any legitimacy.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1791-french-legislative-election] The absence of issues and declared candidacies - the law recognises nothing between the state and individual citizens - favours the control of the electoral machine by those who, being in a better position, can then impose their political choices on the various ballots and choose the men.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1791-french-legislative-election] The Constitution of 1791, which had been examined and reexamined relentlessly since August 1789 and from which the Constituents had set themselves the goal of not parting until it was completed, was adopted on 3 September 1791, after more than two years of effort.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1791-french-legislative-election] The National Constituent Assembly had given the country a new administration, organised communal powers and districts where the elections had elected rather young men.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1791-french-legislative-election] It offered the French, who were weary of unrest, anxiety and passion, a regime that was fairly favourable to freedom - enough for the supporters of the counter-revolution to want to overthrow it - even if it did not guarantee them the fullness of human rights.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1791-french-legislative-election] On 16 May 1791, the Constituents decreed that none of their members could stand for re-election in the next legislature; the new deputies were therefore new men who would be responsible for implementing the new Constitution.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1791-french-legislative-election] The electoral law adopted by the National Constituent Assembly on 4 December 1789 divided citizens into two categories: "active" citizens, who paid taxes and had the right to vote, and "passive" citizens, who did not pay taxes and could not vote.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1791-french-legislative-election] Women**^** and servants could not vote or stand as candidates, nor could citizens in a state of indictment, bankruptcy or insolvency.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1791-french-legislative-election] In these circumstances, the exercise of suffrage, whatever the system, "censal or universal", was a matter for the minorities whose candidates competed for votes.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1791-french-legislative-election] Michel Vovelle noted that it is difficult to estimate French participation in politics during the Revolution because electoral systems differed, suffrage education was difficult and sources of information were inadequate.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1791-french-legislative-election] Nonetheless, most historians agree today that the number of voters excluded by the census remained fairly low; it seems that in rural areas most citizens were active citizens, unlike in the cities where no more than a third of men could vote.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1791-french-legislative-election] The number of citizens commonly accepted as being able to go to the polls is estimated at nearly 4.3 million, compared with 3 million who cannot.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1791-french-legislative-election] However, Jacques Godechot warns that these figures have never been seriously evaluated.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1791-french-legislative-election] Around 4.3 million men voted in the election.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1791-french-legislative-election] There were no formal political parties, although informal groups such as the Feuillants, Jacobins and the Réunion club emerged.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1791-french-legislative-election] While later sources make claims about membership figures for groups and assign alternative names to them, including Girondistes, Lamethistes or Constitutionnels, the sources do not list the membership of the groups.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1791-french-legislative-election] Out of the seven roll call votes held during the Assembly's term, 278 of the 767 members cast 'no' votes to all, while 242 voted 'yes' to all.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1791-french-legislative-election] The newly elected Assembly convened for the first time on 1 October.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1792-french-national-convention-election] Legislative elections were held in France in August and September 1792 to elect deputies to the National Convention.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1792-french-national-convention-election] Primary elections to elect members of electoral colleges were held in August, with the electoral colleges subsequently voting from 2 to 19 September.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1792-french-national-convention-election] The elections established the nation's first government without the monarch, Louis XVI.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1792-french-national-convention-election] On 20 September the Convention gathered for the first time.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1792-french-national-convention-election] From 26 August the candidates were elected by an electoral college; royalist and Girondin candidates were boycotted.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1792-french-national-convention-election] On the same day news reached Paris that the Prussian army had occupied Longwy.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1792-french-national-convention-election] On 28 August the assembly ordered a curfew for the next two days.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1792-french-national-convention-election] The city gates were closed; all communication with the country was stopped.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1792-french-national-convention-election] On 29 August the Prussians attacked Verdun.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1792-french-national-convention-election] When this news arrived it escalated panic in the capital; the situation was highly critical.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1792-french-national-convention-election] In the afternoon of 2 September the September Massacres began.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1792-french-national-convention-election] The electoral colleges voted from 2 to 19 September and lasted three weeks.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1792-french-national-convention-election] To be an elector a citizen had to be over 21, resident one year in his department and not a domestic servant.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1792-french-national-convention-election] An elector could stand as a candidate in any constituency.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1792-french-national-convention-election] To be a delegate or a deputy an elector had to be over 25.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1792-french-national-convention-election] If at the first ballot no candidate received an absolute majority of votes cast, there was to be a second ballot at which only the top two candidates of the first could compete.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1792-french-national-convention-election] According to Malcolm Crook, "Evidence of orchestrated attempts to intimidate rivals is not hard to find." In Paris the sections accepted a proposal by Robespierre four a two stage screening process that was initially targeted at monarchists but ended up excluding all Girondins.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1792-french-national-convention-election] Around 3,360,000 voters participated in the elections.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1792-french-national-convention-election] An absolute majority of the male deputies elected belonged to the *Marais* party, a political faction of vague but largely moderate policies.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1792-french-national-convention-election] Around 136 of the elected legislators joined the Jacobin club.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1792-french-national-convention-election] The Convention met for the first time on 21 September.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1792-french-national-convention-election] Jérôme Pétion de Villeneuve of the Girondins was elected President of the Convention, while Girondins secured most of the posts in the secretariat.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1792-french-national-convention-election] However, the elections preceded the fall of the Girondins as a political faction, mainly because of the political and social unrest following the war started by the Girondin-dominated government in the spring of 1792.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1793-french-constitutional-referendum] A constitutional referendum was held in France in 1973 and 1974.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1793-french-constitutional-referendum] While most voting took place in July 1793, the last day of voting was not until 4 April 1794 when residents of Châteaulin voted.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1793-french-constitutional-referendum] The new constitution was approved by over 99% of voters.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1793-french-constitutional-referendum] However, due to the 13 Vendémiaire, the constitution was never enacted.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1793-french-constitutional-referendum] Due to the ongoing Reign of Terror no official result was never published.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1793-french-constitutional-referendum] René Baticle collated a best estimate of the figures after reviewing the available minutes from assembly meetings; however, of the 5–6,000 assemblies, over 400 failed to transmit their results or figures.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1795-french-legislative-election] Legislative elections were held in France between 12 and 21 October 1795 (20 to 29 Vendémiaire, Year IV) to elect one-third of the members of the Council of Five Hundred and the Council of Ancients, the lower and upper houses of the legislature.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1795-french-legislative-election] The elections were held in accordance with the Constitution of the Year III and the first under the French Directory.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1795-french-legislative-election] Under the Constitution of the Year III, the Directory (*Directoire*) was established, which was a mix of the two former constitutions (1791 and 1793).
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1795-french-legislative-election] The Directory was split into two branches (upper house, the Council of Ancients made up of independent senior politicians; and the lower house, the Council of Five Hundred, which was elected by land owning tax paying men), with a third executive (the Directory Body).
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1795-french-legislative-election] The new system is seen by many historians as imitating the British parliamentary system, while expanding on what is now known as the French system of a separate executive and assembly, which work in conjunction (this being a mix of parliamentary and presidential known as semi-presidentialism).
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1795-french-legislative-election] With the approaching election, the Royalists (known collectively as the Monarchists) hope to take advantage of the elections and see a return to the monarchy and campaign together in many regions.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1795-french-legislative-election] Fearing a monarchist outcome, the Republicans (Jacobins, Thermidorians, and the Montagnards) passed a law, known as the two-thirds decree, which saw each of houses of the directory contain those many members from the convention.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1795-french-legislative-election] Following the 13 Vendémiaire royalist insurrection, the two-thirds principle became a hated law by members of the royalist and anti-radical parties.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1795-french-legislative-election] 1795 began seeing a large swing in support of constitutional royalists, now known as Clichyens, named after the Clichy Club, especially following the Reign of Terror and failures of the government of the French Constitution of 1793.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1795-french-legislative-election] The Royalists were also divided on the future, with the Absolutists (later known as the Ultra-Royalists) preferring a return to the absolute *ancien régime* under Louis, Count of Provence (future Louis XVIII), and supported the now two-year old Quiberon expedition.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1795-french-legislative-election] The Constitutionalists (later represented by the Orléanists and known as the Liberals or Doctrinaires) favoured a constitutional monarchy supporting individual rights and property in addition to freedoms and fair elections.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1795-french-legislative-election] The constitutionalists later began meeting at the Clichy Club, hence the new name, in addition to their nickname, the Clichyens.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1795-french-referendums] The official result was more than 95% in favor of the new constitution.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1795-french-referendums] Of the seven million eligible voters, only 4.49% of voters cast valid votes.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1797-french-legislative-election] Legislative elections were held in France between 21 March and 2 April 1797 to elect one-third of the members of the Council of Five Hundred and the Council of Ancients, the lower and upper houses of the legislature, which were under the Directory.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1797-french-legislative-election] Following the events of the Conspiracy of Equals, the Jacobins and Montagnards lost their majority in the house, due to their support of François-Noël Babeuf.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1797-french-legislative-election] This led to a massive pro-Royalist push in the country, which increased with the impending end to the War of the First Coalition.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1797-french-legislative-election] Though the Royalists disagreed on who they would want to see as the proper pretender to the throne, they did in-fact agree that legally being elected would be the only means which they would re-establish the monarchy.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1797-french-legislative-election] Then, they would call for the dissolution of the Directory, but see the recreation of the Constitution of 1791 with a new National Assembly.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1797-french-legislative-election] The Royalists were also divided on the future however, with the Absolutists (later known as the Ultra Royalists) preferring a return to the absolute *Ancien Régime* under Louis, Count of Provence (future Louis XVIII) and supported the now two-year old Quiberon Expedition.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1797-french-legislative-election] The 'Constitutionalists' (later known as the Liberals or Doctrinaires) favoured a constitutional monarchy in addition to supporting individual rights and property in addition to freedoms and fair elections.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1797-french-legislative-election] The constitutionalists later began meeting at the 'Clichy Club', hence the new name, in addition to their nickname, the 'Clichyens'.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1797-french-legislative-election] The elections saw royalists gain a supermajority, beyond what had been expected.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1797-french-legislative-election] The 260 newly elected members consisted of 182 constitutional monarchists, 34 republicans (of which 16 were left-wing republicans) and 44 whose position was unclear.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1797-french-legislative-election] Only 11 of the 216 outgoing members who stood for re-election were re-elected.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1797-french-legislative-election] The republicans included two new Jacobins, Joseph Bonaparte and Jean-Baptiste Jourdan.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1797-french-legislative-election] In addition to the nearly 200 new seats taken by the pro-royalists, there were around 100 other royalist deputies already present and more than 130 other deputies likely to accept a constitutional monarchy.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1797-french-legislative-election] Less than six months after the election, fearing a return to the monarchy, the Coup of 18 Fructidor removed all those accused of being "pro-Monarchist" or those who had supported those deputies.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1797-french-legislative-election] According to most historians, the coup marked the beginning of the "Second Directory period" which is described as the "Authoritarian Directory".
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1984-european-parliament-election-in-france] European Parliament elections were held in France on 17 June 1984.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1984-european-parliament-election-in-france] Four parties were able to win seats: an alliance of the centre right Union for French Democracy and the Gaullist Rally for the Republic, the Socialist Party and the French Communist Party, and the Front National.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1984-european-parliament-election-in-france] 56.7% of the French population turned out on election day.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1984-european-parliament-election-in-france] The result was the first time the far-right Front National obtained important results – this time 10.8% and close to the declining French Communist Party.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election-in-france/1984-european-parliament-election-in-france] Jonah Birch argues in *Jacobin* that the FN's rise in popularity was caused by the Socialists abandoning their Keynesian platform the previous year and instead pursuing policies of austerity.
